Python coding style preferences

Module structure & imports

Every file starts with a one-liner """Module for ...""" docstring.
Import order: standard library → third-party → internal (src.*), each group separated by a blank line. No wildcard imports. typing imports go in the stdlib block.
Commonly used packages are imported under standard aliases: pygame → pg, pandas → pd, numpy → np, random → rd. Use the alias consistently throughout the file — never mix pygame.X and pg.X.
In entry-point functions like main(), all imports live inside the function body, not at the module top level.

Class design

Config models use Pydantic, subclassing a shared ConfiguredBaseModel with extra="forbid". Never plain dicts or dataclasses for structured config.
Related config fields are grouped into nested inner classes inside the root model, each also extending ConfiguredBaseModel.
Classes that handle loading/saving are separate from classes that use the data.
__init__ unpacks config into named instance attributes, grouped with short # Category section comments. Only frequently-used values get flattened; everything else stays on self.config.

Docstrings & comments

Methods get an intent paragraph starting on the line immediately after the opening """, then a numbered list of steps, then Args and Returns blocks. Only include an Args block if the method has parameters beyond self; only include a Returns block if the method returns a value (i.e. not -> None).
Long methods use short # Category comments as visual section separators, not inline end-of-line comments.
Non-obvious boolean/flag attributes get a docstring directly below them (PEP 257 style), not an inline # comment.
Genuine TODO/refactor notes stay visible in the code with a brief explanation.

Naming conventions

snake_case for everything except classes (PascalCase). No camelCase.
All internal methods use a single leading underscore. Public API surface is narrow and intentional.
Descriptive, self-documenting names. No single-letter variables except loop indices.

Type annotations

Every method has full parameter and return type annotations. -> None is always written explicitly.
Annotate local variables only when the type is non-obvious or deviates from what a reader would expect, or when a variable is declared before assignment.
Use Literal for fields that only accept specific values.

Functions & logic

Pipelines are split across dedicated methods with a clear phase separation (e.g. measure → align → position → draw). Orchestration lives in a higher-level method.
Tree/recursive operations use recursion over iteration, with an explicit early-return base case.
Guard clauses over deep nesting — return early when pre-conditions aren't met.
namedtuple for simple value objects. Plain dict for internal data structures like tree nodes.

Formatting & tooling

Formatter and linter: Ruff, line length 88.
Always add a blank line before a return statement, unless the function body is a single line or the return is inside a conditional block (e.g. if, for, while).
Trailing commas in multi-line expressions.
All file I/O uses context managers (with open(...) as file:).
Project-wide constants live in a dedicated constants.py.
All file paths use pathlib.Path, never raw strings.

Entry point

Always if __name__ == "__main__": main().
main() is the sole orchestration point: loads config, loads data, wires dependencies explicitly. No global state or singletons.